{"id": 90, "ts": 1778776946.9035983, "event": "public_discussion_message", "round": 2, "agent": "agent_3", "message": "From the attributes we have, each candidate shows a mix of strengths and notable gaps:\n**Candidate\u202fA** \u2013 Strong anticipatory judgment, ability to see complex connections, excellent spatial vision and good leadership. However, we have no evidence of stress\u2011handling, decision\u2011making speed, or teamwork/communication, and he is described as unfriendly and a show\u2011off. Those unknowns are risky for long\u2011haul operations where crew coordination and resilience under fatigue are essential.\n**Candidate\u202fB** \u2013 Very conscientious, explicitly handles stress well, and possesses solid technical skills (accurate weather assessment and excellent computer proficiency). These directly support the data\u2011intensive, high\u2011pressure environment of long\u2011distance flights. The only recorded weaknesses are interpersonal \u2013 a tendency to be grumpy, uncooperative and sometimes use the wrong tone. While crew\u2011communication is a concern, the evidence of stress resilience and core technical competence outweighs the interpersonal issues, which can be addressed through training and crew\u2011resource\u2011management.\n**Candidate\u202fC** \u2013 Makes correct decisions quickly and \u201ckeeps calm in a crisis,\u201d indicating good performance under pressure. He also has excellent attention skills and puts concern for others above everything. Yet he has difficulty communicating ideas, is regarded as egocentric, and is not eager to pursue further education. Effective crew coordination on long missions requires clear communication and a collaborative attitude; these deficits are serious for a pilot who must work closely with co\u2011pilots and cabin crew.\n**Candidate\u202fD** \u2013 Excellent problem\u2011solving, concentration, and a strong sense of responsibility, and he can respond adequately to unexpected events. Nevertheless, we lack any data on stress\u2011handling, decision\u2011making speed, or teamwork/communication, and he is described as moody, a loner, and hot\u2011tempered. The missing evidence on resilience and crew interaction, combined with the interpersonal concerns, makes him a less reliable choice for sustained multi\u2011hour flights.\nGiven the long\u2011distance pilot role\u2019s priority on **stress resilience, reliable decision\u2011making under pressure, and technical competence**, Candidate\u202fB is the only pilot with explicit evidence of strong stress handling and the necessary technical skills (weather assessment, computer proficiency). Although his interpersonal style needs improvement, the core operational requirements are met more convincingly than for the other candidates, whose gaps in stress handling, decision speed, or crew communication are more pronounced.\n**Vote:** Candidate\u202fB\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_3\", \"vote\": \"Candidate B\"}"}
